#: src/0344-conventions-galore.md:67
msgid "The current convention for iterator _type_ names is the following:"
msgstr ""

#: src/0344-conventions-galore.md:69
msgid ""
"Iterators require introducing and exporting new types. These types should "
"use the following naming convention:"
msgstr ""

#: src/0344-conventions-galore.md:72
msgid ""
"**Base name**. If the iterator yields something that can be described with a "
"specific noun, the base name should be the pluralization of that noun (e.g. "
"an iterator yielding words is called `Words`). Generic contains use the base "
"name `Items`."
msgstr ""

#: src/0344-conventions-galore.md:77
msgid ""
"**Flavor prefix**. Iterators often come in multiple flavors, with the "
"default flavor providing immutable references. Other flavors should prefix "
"their name:"
msgstr ""

#: src/0344-conventions-galore.md:80
msgid "Moving iterators have a prefix of `Move`."
msgstr ""

#: src/0344-conventions-galore.md:81
msgid ""
"If the default iterator yields an immutable reference, an iterator yielding "
"a mutable reference has a prefix `Mut`."
msgstr ""

#: src/0344-conventions-galore.md:83
msgid "Reverse iterators have a prefix of `Rev`."
msgstr ""

#: src/0344-conventions-galore.md:85
msgid ""
"(These conventions were established as part of [this PR](https://github.com/"
"rust-lang/rust/pull/8090) and later [this one](https://github.com/rust-lang/"
"rust/pull/11001).)"
msgstr ""

#: src/0344-conventions-galore.md:89
msgid ""
"These conventions have not yet been updated to reflect the [recent change]"
"(https://github.com/rust-lang/rfcs/pull/199) to the iterator method names, "
"in part to allow for a more significant revamp. There are some problems with "
"the current rules:"
msgstr ""

#: src/0344-conventions-galore.md:94
msgid ""
"They are fairly loose and therefore not mechanical or predictable. In "
"particular, the choice of noun to use for the base name is completely "
"arbitrary."
msgstr ""

#: src/0344-conventions-galore.md:98
msgid ""
"They are not always applicable. The `iter` module, for example, defines a "
"large number of iterator types for use in the adapter methods on `Iterator` "
"(e.g. `Map` for `map`, `Filter` for `filter`, etc.) The module does not "
"follow the convention, and it's not clear how it could do so."
msgstr ""

#: src/0344-conventions-galore.md:103
msgid ""
"This RFC proposes to instead align the convention with the `iter` module: "
"the name of an iterator type should be the same as the method that produces "
"the iterator."
msgstr ""

#: src/0344-conventions-galore.md:107
msgid "For example:"
msgstr ""

#: src/0344-conventions-galore.md:108
msgid "`iter` would yield an `Iter`"
msgstr ""

#: src/0344-conventions-galore.md:109
msgid "`iter_mut` would yield an `IterMut`"
msgstr ""

#: src/0344-conventions-galore.md:110
msgid "`into_iter` would yield an `IntoIter`"
msgstr ""

#: src/0344-conventions-galore.md:112
msgid ""
"These type names make the most sense when prefixed with their owning module, "
"e.g. `vec::IntoIter`."
msgstr ""

#: src/0344-conventions-galore.md:115
msgid "Advantages:"
msgstr ""

#: src/0344-conventions-galore.md:117
msgid "The rule is completely mechanical, and therefore highly predictable."
msgstr ""

#: src/0344-conventions-galore.md:119
msgid ""
"The convention can be (almost) universally followed: it applies equally well "
"to `vec` and to `iter`."
msgstr ""

#: src/0344-conventions-galore.md:122
msgid "Disadvantages:"
msgstr ""

#: src/0344-conventions-galore.md:124
msgid ""
"`IntoIter` is not an ideal name. Note, however, that since we've moved to "
"`into_iter` as the method name, the existing convention (`MoveItems`) needs "
"to be updated to match, and it's not clear how to do better than `IntoItems` "
"in any case."
msgstr ""

#: src/0344-conventions-galore.md:129
msgid ""
"This naming scheme can result in clashes if multiple containers are defined "
"in the same module. Note that this is _already_ the case with today's "
"conventions.  In most cases, this situation should be taken as an indication "
"that a more refined module hierarchy is called for."
msgstr ""

#: src/0344-conventions-galore.md:136
msgid ""
"An [earlier RFC](https://github.com/rust-lang/rfcs/pull/199) settled the "
"conventions for the \"standard\" iterator methods: `iter`, `iter_mut`, "
"`into_iter`."
msgstr ""

#: src/0344-conventions-galore.md:140
msgid ""
"However, there are many cases where you also want \"nonstandard\" iterator "
"methods: `bytes` and `chars` for strings, `keys` and `values` for maps, the "
"various adapters for iterators."
msgstr ""

#: src/0344-conventions-galore.md:144
msgid "This RFC proposes the following convention:"
msgstr ""

#: src/0344-conventions-galore.md:146
msgid ""
"Use `iter` (and variants) for data types that can be viewed as containers, "
"and where the iterator provides the \"obvious\" sequence of contained items."
msgstr ""

#: src/0344-conventions-galore.md:149
msgid ""
"If there is no single \"obvious\" sequence of contained items, or if there "
"are multiple desired views on the container, provide separate methods for "
"these that do _not_ use `iter` in their name. The name should instead "
"directly reflect the view/item type being iterated (like `bytes`)."
msgstr ""

#: src/0344-conventions-galore.md:154
msgid ""
"Likewise, for iterator adapters (`filter`, `map` and so on) or other "
"iterator-producing operations (`intersection`), use the clearest name to "
"describe the adapter/operation directly, and do not mention `iter`."
msgstr ""

#: src/0344-conventions-galore.md:158
msgid ""
"If not otherwise qualified, an iterator-producing method should provide an "
"iterator over immutable references. Use the `_mut` suffix for variants "
"producing mutable references, and the `into_` prefix for variants consuming "
"the data in order to produce owned values."
msgstr ""

#: src/0344-conventions-galore.md:165
msgid ""
"Some data structures do not wish to provide direct access to their fields, "
"but instead offer \"getter\" and \"setter\" methods for manipulating the "
"field state (often providing checking or other functionality)."
msgstr ""

#: src/0344-conventions-galore.md:169
msgid "The proposed convention for a field `foo: T` is:"
msgstr ""

#: src/0344-conventions-galore.md:171
msgid "A method `foo(&self) -> &T` for getting the current value of the field."
msgstr ""

#: src/0344-conventions-galore.md:172
msgid ""
"A method `set_foo(&self, val: T)` for setting the field. (The `val` argument "
"here may take `&T` or some other type, depending on the context.)"
msgstr ""

#: src/0344-conventions-galore.md:175
msgid ""
"Note that this convention is about getters/setters on ordinary data types, "
"_not_ on [builder objects](http://aturon.github.io/ownership/builders.html). "
"The naming conventions for builder methods are still open."
msgstr ""

#: src/0344-conventions-galore.md:181
msgid ""
"Unlike type parameters, the _names_ of [associated types](https://github.com/"
"rust-lang/rfcs/pull/195) for a trait are a meaningful part of its public API."
msgstr ""

#: src/0344-conventions-galore.md:185
msgid ""
"Associated types should be given concise, but meaningful names, generally "
"following the convention for type names rather than generic. For example, "
"use `Err` rather than `E`, and `Item` rather than `T`."
msgstr ""

#: src/0344-conventions-galore.md:191
msgid "The wiki guidelines have long suggested naming traits as follows:"
msgstr ""

#: src/0344-conventions-galore.md:193
msgid ""
"Prefer (transitive) verbs, nouns, and then adjectives; avoid grammatical "
"suffixes (like `able`)"
msgstr ""

#: src/0344-conventions-galore.md:195
msgid ""
"Trait names like `Copy`, `Clone` and `Show` follow this convention. The "
"convention avoids grammatical verbosity and gives Rust code a distinctive "
"flavor (similar to its short keywords)."
msgstr ""

#: src/0344-conventions-galore.md:199
msgid ""
"This RFC proposes to amend the convention to further say: if there is a "
"single method that is the dominant functionality of the trait, consider "
"using the same name for the trait itself. This is already the case for "
"`Clone` and `ToCStr`, for example."
msgstr ""

#: src/0344-conventions-galore.md:204
msgid "According to these rules, `Encodable` should probably be `Encode`."
msgstr ""

#: src/0344-conventions-galore.md:206
msgid ""
"There are some open questions about these rules; see Unresolved Questions "
"below."
msgstr ""

#: src/0344-conventions-galore.md:208
msgid "Lints"
msgstr ""

#: src/0344-conventions-galore.md:210
msgid ""
"Our lint names are [not consistent](https://github.com/rust-lang/rust/"
"issues/16545). While this may seem like a minor concern, when we hit 1.0 the "
"lint names will be locked down, so it's worth trying to clean them up now."
msgstr ""

#: src/0344-conventions-galore.md:215
msgid ""
"The basic rule is: the lint name should make sense when read as \"allow "
"_lint-name_\" or \"allow _lint-name_ items\". For example, \"allow "
"`deprecated` items\" and \"allow `dead_code`\" makes sense, while \"allow "
"`unsafe_block`\" is ungrammatical (should be plural)."
msgstr ""

#: src/0344-conventions-galore.md:220
msgid "Specifically, this RFC proposes that:"
msgstr ""

#: src/0344-conventions-galore.md:222
msgid ""
"Lint names should state the bad thing being checked for, e.g. `deprecated`, "
"so that `#[allow(deprecated)]` (items) reads correctly. Thus `ctypes` is not "
"an appropriate name; `improper_ctypes` is."
msgstr ""

#: src/0344-conventions-galore.md:226
msgid ""
"Lints that apply to arbitrary items (like the stability lints) should just "
"mention what they check for: use `deprecated` rather than "
"`deprecated_items`. This keeps lint names short. (Again, think \"allow _lint-"
"name_ items\".)"
msgstr ""

#: src/0344-conventions-galore.md:230
msgid ""
"If a lint applies to a specific grammatical class, mention that class and "
"use the plural form: use `unused_variables` rather than `unused_variable`. "
"This makes `#[allow(unused_variables)]` read correctly."
msgstr ""

#: src/0344-conventions-galore.md:234
msgid ""
"Lints that catch unnecessary, unused, or useless aspects of code should use "
"the term `unused`, e.g. `unused_imports`, `unused_typecasts`."
msgstr ""

#: src/0344-conventions-galore.md:237
msgid "Use snake case in the same way you would for function names."
msgstr ""

#: src/0344-conventions-galore.md:241
msgid ""
"Very occasionally, conventions will require a method to have multiple "
"suffixes, for example `get_unchecked_mut`. When feasible, design APIs so "
"that this situation does not arise."
msgstr ""

#: src/0344-conventions-galore.md:245
msgid ""
"Because it is so rare, it does not make sense to lay out a complete "
"convention for the order in which various suffixes should appear; no one "
"would be able to remember it."
msgstr ""

#: src/0344-conventions-galore.md:249
msgid ""
"However, the _mut_ suffix is so common, and is now entrenched as showing up "
"in final position, that this RFC does propose one simple rule: if there are "
"multiple suffixes including `mut`, place `mut` last."
msgstr ""

#: src/0344-conventions-galore.md:255
msgid ""
"It is not currently possible to define inherent methods directly on basic "
"data types like `char` or slices. Consequently, `libcore` and other basic "
"crates provide one-off traits (like `ImmutableSlice` or `Char`) that are "
"intended to be implemented solely by these primitive types, and which are "
"included in the prelude."
msgstr ""

#: src/0344-conventions-galore.md:261
msgid ""
"These traits are generally _not_ designed to be used for generic "
"programming, but the fact that they appear in core libraries with such basic "
"names makes it easy to draw the wrong conclusion."
msgstr ""

#: src/0344-conventions-galore.md:265
msgid ""
"This RFC proposes to use a `Prelude` suffix for these basic traits. Since "
"the traits are, in fact, included in the prelude their names do not "
"generally appear in Rust programs. Therefore, choosing a longer and clearer "
"name will help avoid confusion about the intent of these traits, and will "
"avoid namespace pollution."
msgstr ""

#: src/0344-conventions-galore.md:270
msgid ""
"(There is one important drawback in today's Rust: associated functions in "
"these traits cannot yet be called directly on the types implementing the "
"traits. These functions are the one case where you would need to mention the "
"trait by name, today. Hopefully, this situation will change before 1.0; "
"otherwise we may need a separate plan for dealing with associated functions.)"
msgstr ""

#: src/0344-conventions-galore.md:276
msgid "Error messages"
msgstr ""

#: src/0344-conventions-galore.md:278
msgid ""
"Error messages -- including those produced by `fail!` and those placed in "
"the `desc` or `detail` fields of e.g. `IoError` -- should in general be in "
"all lower case. This applies to both `rustc` and `std`."
msgstr ""

#: src/0344-conventions-galore.md:282
msgid ""
"This is already the predominant convention, but there are some "
"inconsistencies."
msgstr ""

#: src/0344-conventions-galore.md:284
msgid "Alternatives"
msgstr ""

#: src/0344-conventions-galore.md:288
msgid ""
"The iterator type name convention could instead basically stick with today's "
"convention, but using suffixes instead of prefixes, and `IntoItems` rather "
"than `MoveItems`."
msgstr ""

#: src/0344-conventions-galore.md:292
msgid "Unresolved questions"
msgstr ""

#: src/0344-conventions-galore.md:294
msgid ""
"How far should the rules for trait names go? Should we avoid \"-er\" "
"suffixes, e.g. have `Read` rather than `Reader`?"
msgstr ""
